01:30:54.560 --> 01:30:57.060
because he hadn't liked

01:30:57.060 --> 01:30:59.380
learned to appreciate our kind of beer,

01:31:00.480 --> 01:31:01.120
and

01:31:03.560 --> 01:31:05.760
I mean, he understood through that

01:31:06.380 --> 01:31:08.340
a dedicated boozer

01:31:08.340 --> 01:31:10.840
isn't put off a drink just because

01:31:10.840 --> 01:31:12.380
it doesn't taste very nice,

01:31:15.700 --> 01:31:18.900
and sometimes we have to force ourselves,

01:31:19.340 --> 01:31:22.980
and it's quite often in my life

01:31:22.980 --> 01:31:24.420
things I might enjoy myself

01:31:24.420 --> 01:31:25.880
and going through hell,

01:31:28.720 --> 01:31:31.760
and I don't want to run over time

01:31:31.760 --> 01:31:35.080
on perhaps a lot of trivial aspects

01:31:35.080 --> 01:31:37.520
of what we were talking about this evening,

01:31:38.060 --> 01:31:40.480
but I got one fine beer store about Jim

01:31:41.120 --> 01:31:44.060
and it goes back to the time

01:31:44.060 --> 01:31:46.840
two years ago when four

01:31:47.540 --> 01:31:50.180
SCF riders were commissioned

01:31:50.180 --> 01:31:51.720
by the Arts Council of Great Britain

01:31:51.720 --> 01:31:54.940
to do a week-long tour of the Northeast,

01:31:55.360 --> 01:31:55.860
giving time to the people

01:31:55.860 --> 01:31:56.180
and folks,

01:31:58.040 --> 01:32:01.280
and Mark Adelard was one who was there,

01:32:02.440 --> 01:32:05.300
and then one or two nights in that week

01:32:05.760 --> 01:32:09.380
Mark and I put away quite a lot of beer

01:32:09.380 --> 01:32:10.320
and other drinks,

01:32:11.420 --> 01:32:13.960
and we were further enough,

